******
[3] Madurai district (southern Tamil Nadu)
Date: Wed 4 Dec 2013
Source: Times of India [edited]
http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-12-04/madurai/44755922_1_fmd-forest-officials-villages


The threat of foot and mouth disease (FMD) reported among cattle has forced officials to take preventive measures in the villages surrounding the forest areas, especially the ones in the fringe areas of wildlife sanctuaries in the south.

With support from the respective district administrations, the forest officials in the locality have been conducting veterinary camps in the bordering villages over the last week. The veterinary camps are being undertaken in 10 villages bordering Srivilliputhur Grizzled Squirrel Sanctuary, 20 villages near Kalakkad, Mundanthurai Tiger Reserve (KMTR), while camps are proposed for Megamalai Wildlife Sanctuary in Theni and Kodaikanal Wildlife Sanctuary.

Chinnamanur region has been identified as being vulnerable due to its proximity to Megamalai sanctuary, and the 2nd round of vaccination will be undertaken in the region, officials said.

[Byline: J Arockiaraj]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[For the location of Madurai district, see map at http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/TN_Districts_Madurai.gif/250px-TN_Districts_Madurai.gif.

It seems that the FMDV-O epizootic which has been reportedly circulating in 4 of India's southern states, namely Kamataka, Kerala, Tamil Nadu, and Andhra Pradesh, is continuing its spread in spite of the measures applied.

Since FMD is long known to be endemic in India, there is no official obligation to immediately report new outbreaks to the OIE, authoritative information becoming publicly available twice a year from the required 6-monthly summarising reports. However, in view of the seemingly unusual dimensions of the current epizootic in India, probably due to a new strain/genotype, the partial and sometimes contradictory reports from the local government, but mainly from unofficial sources, are short of providing an accurate picture of the unfolding FMD situation there. An interim official report from the central authorities would be helpful and appreciated (including disease distribution, epidemiological data, number of cases and mortalities, control measures including vaccination coverage, and vaccine-strains used).

According to available information (see previous posts in this thread), the outbreak is caused by an FMDV serotype O strain which has been identified as topotype 'ME-SA', Genotype/strain 'Ind-2001 (KAR-13)'.

The same strain has recently been identified in samples submitted to the WRLFMD from affected cattle in Libya and Saudi Arabia. The circulation of the same virus strain in such distant locations is worrying. It is somewhat reminiscent of the early stages of the FMDV-O epizootic of 2000, when another serotype-O strain, the Pan Asia strain, was initially reported from Asia (Japan, S. Korea, Mongolia) and became pandemic, spreading to Africa and eventually Europe.

FMDV serotype O outbreaks have recently been reported from Israel (on the Syrian-Lebanese border) and from the Palestinian authority (Jericho, adjacent to the Jordanian border, yet to be officially reported to the OIE). Their genetic profiles, including their interrelationship, are not yet known. Hopefully, samples have been forwarded to the reference laboratory. - Mod.AS

A ProMED-mail HealthMap can be accessed at http://healthmap.org/r/2kP3.]
